## Migration: `TimedExecutor` to .NET 8

### Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | ❌ Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | ❌ Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `ThreadAbortException` | ❌ Never raised |

`Thread.Abort` was removed because it corrupts app state — it can interrupt code mid-write to shared resources, skip `finally` blocks, and leave locks held.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a cooperative cancellation timeout.
    /// The delegate must observe the <see cref="CancellationToken"/> to stop promptly.
    /// </summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work,
        TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Synchronous overload for callers that can't go async.
    // The work delegate MUST still observe the CancellationToken.
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, T> work,
        TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

        try
        {
            // .WaitAsync throws on timeout even if the inner task is stuck
            return task.WaitAsync(timeout).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (TimeoutException)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Usage

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// Async (preferred)
var result = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(
    async ct =>
    {
        await Task.Delay(500, ct);      // ct is observed here
        return 42;
    },
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// Sync — CPU-bound work checking the token
var value = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct =>
    {
        for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
        {
            ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // cooperative check
            // ... do work ...
        }
        return 99;
    },
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(3));
```

### Key Pitfalls

1. **Cooperative cancellation is mandatory.** If the delegate ignores the `CancellationToken`, `.WaitAsync()` will unblock your caller but the work keeps running on a thread-pool thread — it just becomes fire-and-forget. There is no safe equivalent to `Abort()`.

2. **Don't wrap sync-over-async with `.Result`.** Use `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` to get a single exception instead of `AggregateException`, or go fully async.

3. **`Task.WaitAsync(timeout)`** (added in .NET 6) is critical — without it, `await task` alone blocks forever if the token isn't observed. It gives you the "caller escapes" semantics that `Thread.Join(timeout)` + `Abort()` used to provide, minus the forced kill.

4. **Unobserved tasks can leak.** If your work allocates expensive resources (DB connections, file handles), make it token-aware or wrap it with a `finally` block so cleanup happens even on cancellation.
